Hey anon, another writefag here who also has crippling ADD (no 'H' interestingly), and regularly runs into motivational issues (hence the massive posts here as opposed to making progress on my own stuff).

Having similar issues, I figured I'd share what's worked for me. When you lose the drive* to write, it's usually best to force yourself to stay away from it for a week (maybe two). When you do, commit to a specific period of time. Don't pull up your story. Don't look at it, DON'T PICK AT IT. If the itch to write comes back, good! Let it build for a while. You'll need it to get back up on plane when you start writing. If stepping away from it does nothing for you, it could be that you don't actually want to write something. If that bothers you, try to think on why? Figuring out why you /REALLY/ want to write goes a long way to helping you make it happen. "If you have a why, the how will take care of itself." And all that happy horse shit.

If you still have the drive, the general advice given here holds true. Outlining is your bestest friend in the whole world, at least for a first pass. It lets you big picture and organically (read nonlinearly) drill down into actions, speech, and detail. Drill deep enough in your outline and you'll find yourself a formatting away from completed writing. Let me know if you want more info on this.

Lock some time into your day to work on writing. Schedule it. If you can, try to lock yourself out of distractions. Even the act of trying to constrain yourself (E.G. Turning off WiFi on your computer so you can't just fuck around on the net) will go a long way towards getting you in the right headspace.

*Not to be confused with motivation. As the other Anon has so went stated, you can be completely unmotivated and still feel the drive to write nagging at the back of your mind. You can push through a lack of motivation with discipline, but all the discipline in the world won't help if you don't have a reason to exercise it.

Anonymous Fri 18 Jan 2019 22:32:32 No.20730762 Report
Quoted By: >>20730844
>>20730116
But in terms of what, writing or content? The big 5 will publish anything with a premise they believe is worth selling and edit the hell out of it so that it meets their standards of quality. Editing is largely why so many authors choose to go indie. A work that is ultimately published is just the final draft of a long series of compromises between the author and his or her publisher that will always handily favor the latter. Quality isn't the issue because that's what professional editing is for (this is a reason why writers gravitate toward other writers). What would you do if your publisher sent back your draft with notes saying that aspects of your protagonist's political compass "aren't consistent with today's thinking - will negatively impact sales," and all references to those convictions need to be edited out? It's going to make justifying his struggle against an authoritarian entity extremely difficult to explain; they add that you should make it more of a personal vendetta, maybe for killing his/her father or something ("Just a suggestion!" is written in parentheses under that). So now, to be published, you need to fundamentally change him/her in ways you never intended. Also, there's a footnote at the bottom by your editor, popular and respected New York Times reviewer Larry Goldstein, that says he's "strongly recommending" you consider making the protagonist or one of the protagonist's closest friends gay.

That's what being edited so that your work meets a "certain standard of quality" and being published by a major publisher is really like. Now, once you're established ala J.K. Rowling, you'll enjoy a little more autonomy. However, you'll need to accept and effect your publisher's wishes for your first several books before your readers will ever get to enjoy any stories actually written by you alone. Alternatively, you can hire a professional editor and just publish through Amazon which, you're right, anybody and their dog can do.
